## Summary

Implements agent-scoped Policy overlays under `scopes.agents.<scopeName>` for the policy sections whose evidence is already attributable to runtime agent ids: `tools` and `agents.workspace`.

Each named scope lists the runtime agent ids it applies to with `agentIds`. The scope name is descriptive only; matching uses normalized OpenClaw agent ids, not display names. Multiple scope blocks may target the same agent when they govern different fields, but the same effective agent cannot receive the same scoped policy field from more than one scope block.

The overlay model is additive: top-level `tools.*` and `agents.workspace` claims still run, while scoped `tools` and `agents.workspace` blocks can add stricter claims and emit their own findings against the same observed config. Unsupported scoped sections and unsupported scoped `tools` keys are rejected rather than silently ignored.

`tools.alsoAllow.expected` is supported as an exact-list conformance claim. It reports missing expected additive grants and unexpected extra additive grants, including the empty-list case where policy expects no `alsoAllow` entries.

Example:

```jsonc
{
  "tools": {
    "exec": { "allowHosts": ["gateway", "sandbox"] },
    "alsoAllow": { "expected": [] }
  },
  "agents": {
    "workspace": { "allowedAccess": ["none", "ro"] }
  },
  "scopes": {
    "agents": {
      "release-workspace": {
        "agentIds": ["release-agent", "support-agent"],
        "agents": {
          "workspace": { "allowedAccess": ["none", "ro"] }
        }
      },
      "release-tools": {
        "agentIds": ["release-agent"],
        "tools": {
          "exec": { "allowHosts": ["node"] },
          "alsoAllow": { "expected": ["read"] }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

In this example, `release-agent` receives both the shared `release-workspace` claim and the narrower `release-tools` claim, while `support-agent` only receives the shared workspace claim. That demonstrates overlapping scopes without duplicating the same effective policy field for the same agent.

## Verification

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.test.ts extensions/policy/src/cli.test.ts -- --reporter=dot` -> 2 files, 175 tests passed
- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check docs/cli/policy.md docs/plugins/reference/policy.md docs/plan/policy-agent-scoped-overlays.md extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.ts extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.test.ts`
- `pnpm exec oxlint extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.ts extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.test.ts`
- `pnpm docs:check-mdx docs/cli/policy.md docs/plugins/reference/policy.md docs/plan/policy-agent-scoped-overlays.md`
- `git diff --check FETCH_HEAD...HEAD`

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: Policy conformance can now express stricter workspace and tool posture claims for named policy scopes that target explicit runtime agent ids without weakening deployment-wide policy claims.

Real environment tested: WSL Ubuntu 24.04 checkout at `/root/src/openclaw-85817`, rebased on current `main`, using a disposable `OPENCLAW_HOME`, disposable `OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH`, and a disposable `policy.jsonc` under `/tmp`.

Exact command run after this patch:

```bash
OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH="$proof/openclaw.json" \
  OPENCLAW_HOME="$proof/home" \
  OPENCLAW_DISABLE_AUTO_UPDATE=1 \
  node --import tsx src/entry.ts policy check --json
```

The disposable config had global `tools.exec.host=sandbox`, global `tools.alsoAllow=["read","cron"]`, `release-agent` with `workspaceAccess=rw`, `tools.exec.host=node`, and `tools.alsoAllow=["read","gateway"]`, plus `support-agent` with matching workspace and sandbox exec host. The policy file had global workspace/tool requirements plus `scopes.agents.release-agent-lockdown` for stricter workspace, exec host, and `alsoAllow.expected` rules targeting only `release-agent`.

Redacted output summary:

```json
{
  "ok": false,
  "findings": [
    {
      "checkId": "policy/agents-workspace-access-denied",
      "ocPath": "oc://openclaw.config/agents/list/#0/sandbox/workspaceAccess",
      "requirement": "oc://policy.jsonc/agents/workspace/allowedAccess"
    },
    {
      "checkId": "policy/agents-workspace-access-denied",
      "ocPath": "oc://openclaw.config/agents/list/#0/sandbox/workspaceAccess",
      "requirement": "oc://policy.jsonc/scopes/agents/release-agent-lockdown/agents/workspace/allowedAccess"
    },
    {
      "checkId": "policy/tools-exec-host-unapproved",
      "ocPath": "oc://openclaw.config/agents/list/#0/tools/exec/host",
      "requirement": "oc://policy.jsonc/scopes/agents/release-agent-lockdown/tools/exec/allowHosts"
    },
    {
      "checkId": "policy/tools-also-allow-missing",
      "ocPath": "oc://openclaw.config/agents/list/#0/tools/alsoAllow",
      "requirement": "oc://policy.jsonc/scopes/agents/release-agent-lockdown/tools/alsoAllow/expected"
    },
    {
      "checkId": "policy/tools-also-allow-unexpected",
      "ocPath": "oc://openclaw.config/agents/list/#0/tools/alsoAllow",
      "requirement": "oc://policy.jsonc/scopes/agents/release-agent-lockdown/tools/alsoAllow/expected"
    }
  ]
}
```

Observed result after fix: the real `openclaw policy check --json` path loaded the scoped policy file, emitted both global and agent-scoped findings for `release-agent`, and did not emit `release-agent-lockdown` scoped findings for `support-agent`.

What was not tested: live channel or sandbox runtime enforcement; this PR intentionally adds Policy conformance/audit grammar, not runtime enforcement.

